{"/service/ndnp/mb/batch_mb_basil_ver01/data/sn83020847/00517170847/1946020701/0083.xml":{"full_text":"RECOVERY FOLLOWS\nPROFIT-TAKING ON\nEXCHANGE\u2019S FLOOR\nDay Is Mostly a Repetition\nof One Before Philip\nMorris Mystery Seems to\nGet Even Deeper\nWall Street Correspondenee\nThe Republican\nNew York, Feb, I\u2014Today\u2019sl\u2014Today\u2019s slock\nmarket was a repetition of whal hap\npened yesterday when early profit\ntaking was followed by recovery. To\nday industrials made their low for\nthe day In the first hour, after which\nthere was sustained recovery, most\npivotal* closing at the highs of the\nday with gains of fractions or a point\nor more from last night. Chemicals\nwere outstanding with du Pont clos\ning up 6*4. Ralls mostly showed only\nirregular fractional chang' v.\nSelling pressure In Ph.dp Morris,\nwhich carried the price of the stock\nfrom Monday's closing of 71 to yes\nterday\u2019s 55*4. new low for 1915-46\nagainst the high for that period of\n74, appeared today to have dried up.\nToday the slock opened at 56 and\nby midday the price was 57H. As\nget, however, there Is still mystery\nsurrounding the break in Philip Mor\nris which started Tuesday with a\nSudden decline that day of 11 points.\nThe Tuesday decline in Philip Mor\nris followed the news that after the\nclose of the market that day a sec\nondary ottering of 40.000 shares\nwould be made. Following the nose-1\ndive of 11 points, it was announced I\nthat the ottering had been with\ndrawn. Then things began to happen\nin the news about Philip Morris.\nSales Slump Noted\nFirst it was announced that the\npublic offering of $15,000,000 20-year\nper cent debentures at 103. which\u201d\nhad been underwritten by two bank\ning houses, had been withdrawn.\nNext. Philip Morris announced that\nholders of the common stock who\nhad recently subscribed to new pre\nferred stock could undo the transac\ntion if they so desired. Next, the\ncompany announced that a drastic\ndecline had occurred in sales during\nthe five months ended with Decem\nber.\nToday the mystery in Philip Morris\nWas increased by announcements by\nAmerican Tobacco and R. J. Reynolds\nTobacco that their sales of cigarets\nhad continued to advance over the\nlike period of 1944. These announce\nments were undoubtedly inspired by\nthe selling pressure that started in\nthe stocks of alt cigaret manufac\nturers following Tuesday\u2019s break of\n11 points in Philip Morris. If sales\nby American Tobacco and R. .1.\nReynolds continued to increase, people\nin Wall street were asking today,\nwhy should the sales of Philip Mor\nris decline?\nIt is a pretty safe guess that in\nthe matter of sales American and\nReynolds are in the same boat with\nPhilip Morris, which reported that\nIts earnings for five months had de\nclined compared with previous\nmonths. American and Reynolds re\nported their sales continuing to gain\nover the like months of ihe previous\nyear. That could be true with cur\nrent sales below those of earlier\nmonths.\nAll Famine's Are Donn\nWhat has happened recently in\nmonthly earnings of Philip Morris s\nnot any different than what has hap\npened in industry as a whole. As\nlong as record wartime earnings con\ntinued. corporations could take care\nof high overhead. But it was a dif\nferent story when government war\nRiders were canceled and labor\ntroubles began to slow down civilian\nproduction.\nAttention was called in this column\nyesterday to what took place in rail\ntoad earnings for December. As long\nas the railroads had the benefit of\nwartime earnings, higher operating\ncosts could be absorbed. But the\nhigh spot in the December earnings\nis the heavy loss in gross, resulting\nin a drastic' cut in net income. When\nGeneral Motors and the United States\nSteel Corp, report their earnings for\nthe strike period, shareholders of\ncorporations will find out just how\nprofits can be smacked around when\nsales decline.\nPor corporations in general whose\nearnings have not been reduced by\nstrikes the outlook for earnings boils\ndown to how long it will take for the\nadministration to learn that produc\ntion cannot be maintained if\nare increased on top of already high\noperating costs with no increase in\nselling prices. When this lesson is\nlearned, then Washington will be\nconfronted with something real in the\nwav of a problem\u2014how to prevent\nrunawav inflation before production\nbegins to catch up with consumer\ndemand. Tt is the outlook for more\ninflation that makes the stock matket\nS toCk af\nCOMPLETE N. Y TIEUP\nUNLIKELY, RYAN SAYS\nHe Says Longshoremen\nWon\u2019t Work Ships Able to\nDock Without Tugs\nNew Yodk. Jan. 31\u2014< A T)\u2014 Joseph\nP. Ryan, president of the Intel na\ntional Longshoremen's association\n(AF).), today ruled out the possibil\nitv of a complete tieup of New' York s\nmassive harbor as a result of his\nunions support of a tugboat strike\nscheduled Monday.\n\"Bv Sunday night there will be\nplenty of ships at the docks.\" Ryan\nsaid. \u201cThe longshoremen will he\nworking those ships for several days,\nperhaps to the end of next week.\nMeanwhile, perhaps the strike will\nhave been settled.\"\nRyan said earlier his 33.000 long\nshoremen w\u2019ould refuse to handle car\ngoes of ships able to dock or sail\nwithout assistance, of tugs, indicating\nan immediate and complete tieup on\nMonday.\nMeanwhile, a spokesman for the\nConsolidated Edison Co. said the\nstrike, involving 3500 tugboat work\ners, would mean a virtual blackout\nof the city by the middle of next\nweek because the company would run\nout of coal for its power plants. He\nadded that the company was depend\nent on stockpiles In New Jersey for\nIts generating plants. New York's\ncoal is floated across the Hudson riv\ner and New York harbor on barges\ntowed by tugboats. Inoperative barges\nwould mean the shutting off of coal\nfor beating as well as for power,\nplants.\nCourt Reverses SEC\nOn Stock Purchases\nWashington, Feb. 4 (A?) The\nfederal court of appeals for the Dis\ntrict of Colombia today reversed a\nruling of Securities comm lesion that\nsale and purchase of stock in a com\npany by its officials could not be per\nmitted during the time a reorganiza\ntion plan wm before the SKC.\nThe commmiaaion. the court said\nIn the holding company case, over\nstepped the. bounds of \u201cadministra\ntive discretion entrusted to it by Con\ngress.\"\nThe rase involved the petition of\nthe Chenery Carp., and others, and\nFINANCIAL'\nthe Federal Water and Gas Corp.,\nall of whom were associated through\nsecurity ownership, to.review an or\nder of the SEC.\nFINLAND GRANTED\n35 MILLION LOAN\nFOR 20-YEAR TERM\nExport-Import Bank Gives\nCredit for Purchase of Re\nconstruction Goods New\nSchedule On Old Loans\nWashington, Jan. 31\u2014(AP)\u2014Fin\nland was granted a $35,000,000 loan\nby the Export-Import hank today to\nenable her to purchase \"urgently\nneeded\" American reconstruction\ngoods.\nWayne C. Taylor, bank president,\nannounced Ihe credit after nearly a\nmonth of negotiations with a Finnish\nfinancial mission in Washington.\nTaylor said the new credit was in\naddition to the special $5,000,000 al\nlotted to Finland last month for pur\nchase of raw cotton in the United\nStates.\nSimultaneously. h\u00bb disclosed that a\nnew schedule for repayment of two\nformer loans to Finland totaling $25,-\n000,000 had been agreed upon. These\ntwo credits had been granted in 1939\nand 1940 to the Finnish-American\nTrading Corp.\u2014a Finnish government\nsubsidiary.\nFinland must repay the new- $35,-\n000,000 lonn in 20 years at an Inter\nest rate which averages 3 per cent.\nYA SEEKING SPACE\nIN PUBLIC HOSPITALS\nU. S. Hospitals Not Big\nEnough to Care for Men\nWith Nonservice Ailments\n\u2014May Rise to 500,000\nPatients\nWashington. Jan. 31\u2014 (AP)\u2014 Th*\neterans administration, already busy\nwith a. big hospital building program,\nstarted making arrangements today\nfor care of former servicemen in civil\nian hospitals.\nOfficials of both the VA and the\nAmerican Legion, none of whom\nwould speak for attribution, said the\nmove followed recent correspondence\nwith the \"White House\u201d\u2014though not\nwith President Truman himself \u2014on\nthe point of how far the government\nshould go in providing care for vet\nerans whose ills were not service con\nnected.\nPresident Truman said at his news\nconference this afternoon that he did\nnt know about any such correspond\nence.\nThe VA and Legion officials\nagreed that the \u201cWhite House\u201d\ncommunication was noncommittal, but\nthey took it as approval for the re\ncent trend of VA policy which had\nbeen toward some degree of liberaliza\ntion.\nThe start on use of civilian hospi\ntal space is being made in Michigan,\nwhere VA announced it was signing\na contract with the Michigan Hos\npital association to make available\nan unspecified number of beds. One\nofficial said the number of beds\nwhich VA might use in all the hospi\ntals covered by the contract \u2019could\nrun into the hundreds, perhaps\nthousands.\u201d\nVA spokesmen have said that if\ncare were, limited to combat or ser\nvice-connected disabilities, the 97 Vet\nerans administration hospitals would\nhave \u2018more than enough space\u201d for\nthe current job.\nApproximately 70 per cent of the\n83.000 now in veterans hospitals are\nnon-service connected. There is a\nwaiting list of 10.000 such cases. VA\nis trying to borrow 40.000 beds from\narmy, navy and private hospitals. It\nhas a $380,000,000 building program\nunder way.\nThe law provides that the govern\nment shall care for all veterans wh(?\ncan trace disability to war or mili\ntary service. Then if additional space\nis available other veterans may be ad\nmitted to government hospitals but\nthey must sign a statement that they\ndo not have funds to pay for a pri\nvate physician or hospital.\nIf hospital service is offered to all\nveterans who report they cannot\nafford to pay for it. VA officials have\nestimated, the case load may climb\nio 500.000 by 1975. They have figured\nthat the number of actually service\nconnected cases probably will never\nrise above 100.000.\nAUTO PRODUCTION MAY\nHIT 15,000 THIS WEEK\nNormal Output Would Be\n100,000 Units Strikes\nBlamed for Decrease\nDetroit, Feb. 3\u2014(APl\u2014Production\nin the nations automobile plants,\nnormally averaging 100 000 units a\nweek at this point, in a new model\nyear, probably will shrink to below\n15,000 vehicles during the coming\nweek, because of the steel and Gen\neral Motors strikes.\nEast week's assemblies. according\nto Ward's automotive report, num\nbered 29,295 units. Close to half the\ntotal came from Ford assembly lines.\nAs a result of the steel strike alone,\nclose to 60,000 car factory employes\nhave been made idle. The General\nMotors strike has idled 175,000 pro\nduction workers and an undetermined\nnumber of men in supplier plants or\ndered to discontinue shipments to GM\nuntil Its 96 closed plants could be re\nopened.\nLocal Securities\nOver-the-counter prices of local\nsecurities furnished by Springfield in\nvestment brokers as of 4 p. m. yester\nday on a nominal basis were as fol\nlows:\u2014\u0964\nBanks\nPrev.\nBid Asked bid\nAgricultural Natl Bk 2V\u00bb 275\nBerkshire Trust Co '2\nGreylock Natl Bk\nMorris Plan Co Spdd 50\nPlttafleld-Third Natl Bk\nTrust Co 1\u2122 >22,\nSpfid Natl Bk 22%\nSpfld Safe Dep A Tr Co ..67\nThird Natl Bk 4 Tr Co 62\nUnion Trust Co 7$\nPublic Service Companies\nKoiyoke Water Power 21 23 20%\nPittsfield Coal Gas 52\nSpfld Gm Light 28% 30% 28%\nWestern Maes. Cos 37% 30%\nIndustrial and Miscellaneous\nBerkshire Fine Spinning 37 30 37\nDo pf HO 111\nRowlee Lunch, Inc pf 9\u201d .0\u00b0\nChapman Valve 30% 52% M\u00bb\nDo pf 133 133\nConsolidated Dry Goode 17\nDo pfd 95 \u201d5\nForbee A Wallace A 48\nGreenfield Tap Die gK pfd 98 98\nMendey Machine 7% 8% 7%\nIndian Motocycle 12 14 12\nLudlow Mfg Amoc 140\nMonarch Life Ins 75 74\nNational Union 10 H\u00bb\nN