%l\n8 Worthing P4M .61 60 H\u00bbi% j\n2 Do cv pr pf 97 98 qg 2\n1 Do pr pf 94% 94% 94%\n.30 W ight Aero 106 KM 104 \u20142\nWrlglev <W> Jr 6\u2019% 81% 81%\n10 Wyand Wor 33% 32% 33%+\nY\n2 Yale Towne .49% 49 49%\n10 York Corp ?8% 28% 26%\n2 Young SA W 33 X 3 33\n2. Youngat Sh T 74% 72% 74 r 1\\\n12 Tdunget Stl Dr 30% 79% 29%\u2014\nX\n3 Zenith Radin 41 46% 41\n31 Zomte ITodukis 13% 13 13% r %l\np*rlenc\u00ab in W.n on. old-\ntlm.r wa. heard to comment thi.\nw.rk, \u25a0\u25a0.tock, ara being bought by\nboth optimise and Opti-\nmist. are bullish on ths postwar busi\nnsw outlook and pessimists are afraid\nof dangerous Inflation.\u201d\nConcern over the outlook for d\u00bbn\ngeroua inflation has been growing\nsteadily ever since the bull stock\nmarket started in 190 from the war\ntime closing low of 92.9 J. Th. av\nerage last Tuesday, a new recovery\nhigh was 205.25. Here Is what Na\ntional City trank here had to say in\nIts October. 1942, regular monthly\nhank letter.\u2014\nMore si money In kpeng\n\u201cA great atep-up In the rate of\ngrowth of the Inflationary forces Is\ntaking place Record breaking Gov\nernment expenditures resulting in a\ncontinued unbalanced budget, ft\npointed out, were increasing bank de\nposits and \u201cgiving the people more\nmoney to spend The sap between\nspendable income and civilian pro\nduction. It was det tared, is the\nsource of the inflationary pressure\non prices\u201d; that \"with the luflatlon\nury pressures now being multiplied,\nthe n\u00bbed of more effective measureA\nto control them is vastly increased\u201d;\nthat \"price advances In any case are\nconsequences of inflation, the causes\nof which are elsewhere\"; that \"pres\nsure is accumulating under \u00bbwn of\nth* price ceilings\".\nIn its October. 190, hank letter,\nthe National City said. \"Thia\ncountry had been through three in\nflationary periods, all within the ex\nperience of men who are active to\nday. and all consisting in simplest\nterms of a period of debt-making\nand distortion of economic relations,\nfollowed by crash, debt-paying and\ndepression.\"\nThe first period, it pointed out, was\nthe inflation of the first World war\nwhich was led by the great rise tn\ncommodity prices due to wartime de\nmands and postwar re, onstructtosi\nneeds; this rise was accompanied,\nwith a lag. by commensurate in\ncreases in wages and by spectacular\nadvances, later to be ruinous, in\nreal estate values.\nIn the second period of inflation\nin the late 1920 s it pointed out the\nfarmer had a small part: that during\nthis period there was no extraordi\nnary rise in wages; that thia period\n\"was essentially a financial inflation\"\naccompanied by credit expansion due\nto the stock market and business\nbooms, to personal extravagance and\noverborrowing.\nThe third period of inflation, it\nwas added, \"is the one upon which\nthe country has now entered.\u201d\n.One lesson learned from the three\nperiods of inflation. It said, is that\nIt produces great distortion in eco\nnomic relations: that another is ttait\nthose who seem to benefit from in\nflation. as owners of commodities or\nland, or speculators in securities or\nproperty, in fact suffer most in the\nensuing catastrophe unless, of course,\nthey cash in their temporary gains\nand pay off their debts\u201d: that \"not\nmany do that, and stop there\u2019\u2019; that\n\"this should warn the groups which\nare trying to get more and more for\nthemselves.\u201d R. L. BARNUM.\nSOCIAL SECURITY\nTAX RISE ADVISED\nHouse Commit tee's Research\nStaff Would Boost It One-\nHalf Per Cent and Extend\nCoverage\nWashington. Jan. so\u2014(APl\u2014The\nHouse ways and means committee\nwas advised by i's reseaa-ch suit to\nday that the social security tax should\nlie increased one-half per cent next\nj ear and coverage be extended to W,-\n000.000 additional workers.\nApproximately $0,000,000 jobs now\nare covered, entitling workers to old\nage and survivors insurance. The\ncommittee's staff of experts would\nhave virtually all jobs covered under\ni plan filed with the group.\nThere no longer is any reason, the\nreport said, why coverage should not\nbe made available to nearly all of the\n9,000.000 self-employed, including farm\nioperators: 4.000.000 agricultural work\niers: f. 409,000 normally in domestic\nservice; 1.100.000 employed by non\nprofit organizations, and millions tn\nother uncovered employment.\nFurther Increase I\u2019roposed\nChairman DoUgMon (D-NC) called\n>ihe commifee to 'meet tomorrow tor\nihe beginning nt a reexamination of\nthe social security law. to determine\nwhat expansions should be made and\nwhat rhe future tax shoul-i be.\nThe staff suggested that the tax on\nemployes' pay and employers' pay\nrolls, now 1 per cent, be boosted in\n194\u201d to 1.5 per rent against each.\nMoreover, it advised that the social\nsecurity levy should increase by an\nother one-half per cent each 10 years\nuntil a 3 per rent maximum rate was\nreached in 197\u201d. This tax covers pay\nments of old-age and survivors' in\nsurance.\nWESTINGHOUSE DENIES\nCONGRESSMEN\u2019S CHARGE\nSays Refusal to Grant Union\nDemand Doesn't Mean Re\nfusal to Bargain\nNew York. Jan. 31 (AP) The\nWestinghouse Electric Co. said toda^\nthe fart that it has not granted a\ni union demand for a $2-a-day wage in\u00ab\nI crease does not mean that the corii\npany has refused to bargain in good\nfaith, as charged by six Philadelphia\ncongres>inen.'\u2019\nThe representatives made the ra\nmark in a statement issued in Wash\nington last njghu They said West*\nfinghouse. along with Genera! Electric\nt'o. and ihe electrical division of Gen\neral YLitors, are defying the demand\nof their workers for a living wage\nand the need of the country for buy-\ning power.\u201d\nWestinghouse said in a statement:\n\u2018The facts are that Westinghouse\nhas met with union representative\non numerous occasions over a period\nof months. The company has\nbeen and remains wi\u00dfing to bargain\nwith its employes, but to capitulate\nto its exorbitant demand would not be\nbargaining.\nGeneral Motors Corp.\nDeclares 75-Cent Dividend\nNew York. Feb. 4 (AP) Di\nrectors of General Motors Corp, de\nclared tmiay a dividend of 75 cents a\nshare on common stock, payable\nMarch Si to holders of record Febru\nary 14.\nAlso ordered during the directors*\nmeeting was the regular quarterly\ndisbursement of II 25 a share on the\n35 preferred stock, payable May 1\n10 holders of record April 8. The divi\ndend on the common was at the same\nrate paid in previous quarters.\nN. Y. GETS 7000 UMTS\nNew York. Jan. 30\u2014(A P)\u2014New\nYork city requests for 7000 emer*\ngency housing units have been ap*\nproved and more than 3000 of them\nare due to be shipped here in about\nrwo weeks. John A. Kervick. regional\ndirector as the Federal Public Hous\ning authority^ said today.\n13","height":"25947","width":"19401"}}
